Predicting the Price of Airbnb in LA

PSTAT131 - Final Project

Sharon Lee

3/5/2023

Introduction

The purpose of this project is to predict the price of Airbnb in Los Angeles.

Airbnb is an online marketplace for short-term home stays. The difference of Airbnb from hotel is that anyone can be host renting out their house and that travelers can experience more localized lodgings in a specific area instead of hotels. As a lot of young people tend to use Airbnb to find an affordable accommodation during trip, the efficiency of cost would be the most important factor to determine whether they want to stay at a certain place or not. So knowing how more expensive the place is than the suggested price can help them to choose the place to stay.

Project Outline

Our plan for this project is to explore multiple models that predict the Airbnb price in LA based on various variables and to find out what variables affect the price the most and the least. I specified the region of the Airbnb as Los Angeles because LA is one of the areas where travelers visit the most in California. Our data is from Inside Airbnb.

Setting Up Models

Now it’s time to move on to building our models. We will perform train/test split, set up and create our recipe, and establish cross-validation for our models.

Train/Test Split

Before we perform our model building, we need to split our data into two separate sets. 90% of our data will be the training set, and the other 10% will be used as the testing set. In our case, it is okay to set 10% of our data as the testing set because we still have more than 4000 observations in the testing set. We are splitting data so that we can use the training set to build our model and use the testing set to check how accurate our model is. We will set our seed to make sure that our random split remains the same every time we work with our models, and also stratify on our response variable, price.

set.seed(20)

airbnb_split <- initial_split(airbnb, prop = 0.9, strata = price)
airbnb_train <- training(airbnb_split)
airbnb_test <- testing(airbnb_split)

Since we will be using the same predictors, model conditions, and response variable, we will build our recipe for all our models. Each model takes this recipe and work with in different methods. We will be using 6 predictors: neighbourhood_group, room_type, minimum_nights, number_of_reviews, calcaulated_host_listings_count, and availability_365. We are excluding neighbourhood because it has too many levels, which would negatively impact performance level of the models. We will dummy-code neighbourhood_group and room_type since they are categorical variables, and then normalize our variables by centering and scaling.

Recipe Building

airbnb_recipe <- recipe(price ~ neighbourhood_group + room_type + minimum_nights +
                          number_of_reviews + calculated_host_listings_count + availability_365,
                        data=airbnb_train) %>%
  step_dummy(neighbourhood_group) %>%
  step_dummy(room_type) %>%
  step_center(all_predictors()) %>%
  step_scale(all_predictors())

prep(airbnb_recipe) %>% bake(airbnb_train)

K-Fold Cross Validation

We will create 10 folds for stratified cross validation. We are stratifying on our response variable, price for a better estimate of the testing accuracy without the issue of imbalanced data.

airbnb_folds <- vfold_cv(airbnb_train, v = 10, strata = price)

Model Building

It’s finally time to build our models. We will try 7 different models to select the best model for our data, and each results will be saved in different file since some models take a long time to run. I will set my metric of performance as Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) because it is one of the most commonly used measurement for regression. The RMSE measures the differences between the actual values and the predictive values, so we are looking for a model with the lowest RMSE.

Each model has a similar process. First, we need to set up the models by specifying the parameter we are tuning, the mode which is regression in our case, and the model engine we are trying to fit.

# LINEAR REGRESSION 
lm_model <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm")

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
# Tuning the number of neighbors
knn_model <- nearest_neighbor(neighbors = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("kknn")

# RIDGE REGRESSION
# Tuning penalty and setting mixture to 0 to specify ridge
ridge_model <- linear_reg(mixture = 0, penalty = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# LASSO REGRESSION
# Tuning penalty and setting mixture to 1 to specify lasso
lasso_model <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = 1) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# ELASTIC NET
# Tuning penalty and mixture
elastic_model <- linear_reg(penalty = tune(), mixture = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("glmnet")

# PRUNE DECISION TREES
# Tuning cost_complexity
tree_model <- decision_tree(cost_complexity = tune()) %>%
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("rpart")

# RANDOM FOREST
# Tuning mtry (number of predictors), trees, and min_n (number of minimum values in each node)
# Don't have to tune min_n (number of minimum values in each node) because our dataset is too large
rf_model <- rand_forest(mtry = tune(), trees = tune()) %>% 
  set_mode("regression") %>% 
  set_engine("ranger", importance = "impurity")

Next, we set up the workflow and add model and recipe. This process will help us a lot when we are trying out a series of models or several different recipes later on.

# LINEAR REGRESSION 
lm_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
knn_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(knn_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# RIDGE REGRESSION
ridge_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(ridge_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# LASSO REGRESSION
lasso_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lasso_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# ELASTIC NET
elastic_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(elastic_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# PRUNE DECISION TREES
tree_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(tree_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

# RANDOM FOREST
rf_workflow <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(rf_model) %>% 
  add_recipe(airbnb_recipe)

The third step is to create a tuning grid to specify the ranges of the parameters to tune and how many levels of each. It helps us find one that performs best by fitting many models with different sets of hyperparameters. We don’t need to create a tuning grid for linear model since it doesn’t have any tuning parameter.

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
knn_grid <- grid_regular(neighbors(range = c(1,10)), levels = 10)

# RIDGE REGRESSION & LASSO REGRESSION
rl_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(0,1)), levels = 10)

# ELASTIC NET
elastic_grid <- grid_regular(penalty(range = c(0,1)), mixture(range = c(0,1)), levels = 10)

# PRUNE DECISION TREES
tree_grid <- grid_regular(cost_complexity(range = c(-3, -1)), levels = 10)

# RANDOM FOREST
rf_grid <- grid_regular(mtry(range = c(1, 6)), trees(range = c(100,300)), levels = 5)

The next step is to fit the models within each fold for each value specified in the tuning grid. For the linear regression, since it doesn’t have any tuning, we will fit the model to the validation set using different function.

# LINEAR REGRESSION
lm_fit <- fit_resamples(lm_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds)

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
knn_tune <- tune_grid(knn_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = knn_grid)

# RIDGE REGRESSION
ridge_tune <- tune_grid(ridge_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = rl_grid)

# LASSO REGRESSION
lasso_tune <- tune_grid(lasso_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = rl_grid)

# ELASTIC NET
elastic_tune <- tune_grid(elastic_workflow,resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = elastic_grid)

# PRUNE DECISION TREES
tree_tune <- tune_grid(tree_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = tree_grid)

# RANDOM FOREST
rf_tune <- tune_grid(rf_workflow, resamples = airbnb_folds, grid = rf_grid)

We need to save the tuned models to an RDA file to avoid rerunning the model.

# K NEAREST NEIGHBOURS
save(knn_tune, file = "knn_tune.rda")

# RIDGE REGRESSION
save(ridge_tune, file = "ridge_tune.rda")

# LASSO REGRESSION
save(lasso_tune, file = "lasso_tune.rda")

# ELASTIC NET
save(elastic_tune, file = "elastic_tune.rda")

# PRUNE DECISION TREES
save(tree_tune, file = "tree_tune.rda")

# RANDOM FOREST
save(rf_tune, file = "rf_tune.rda")

Lastly, let’s load the saved files to analyze their performance.

load(file = "knn_tune.rda")
load(file = "ridge_tune.rda")
load(file = "lasso_tune.rda")
load(file = "elastic_tune.rda")
load(file = "tree_tune.rda")
load(file = "rf_tune.rda")

Model Results

Model Autoplots

We will use the autoplot function to visualize the performance of different hyperparameter values on each model. The measurement of the performance is the RMSE.

K Nearest Neighbors

autoplot(knn_tune)

In this K Nearest Neighbors model, we tuned neighbors at 10 levels. The graph shows that the more number of neighbors we have the model has less RMSE which means that it performs better with more neighbors.

Elastic Net

autoplot(elastic_tune)

For the Elastic Net model, we tuned penalty and mixture at 10 levels. We can find that the model with less penalty and less mixture does better on performance. The RMSE tends to increase as the value of penalty increases, and the change in performance gets larger as the mixture gets larger. When the penalty is 1 which is the lowest, the models with all different mixture have the similar RMSE values, but as the penalty get higher, the difference of performance in mixture get large.

Prune Decision Tree

autoplot(tree_tune)

For Decision Tree model, we set the range of cost-complexity from -3 to -1. Since it is in log_10 scale by default, the range we tuned is from 0.001 to 0.100 at 10 levels. The graph shows that this model performs better when cost-complexity is 0.001. As this value increases, the model tends to have larger RMSE value which means that the model is performing worse.

Random Forest

autoplot(rf_tune, metric="rmse")

For Random Forest model, we didn’t tune min_n since our dataset is large, but mtry and trees are turned at 5 levels. From the graph, the number of trees doesn’t seem to make a difference since all of the graphs tend to overlap each other. On the other hand, the performance of the model gets better as mtry reaches to 4, and the model does worse when mtry is more than 4. So we can say that the model performs the best with 4 randomly selected predictors.

Model RMSE

It’s finally time to compare the results of all of our models by using our metric RMSE. We will create a tibble to display the RMSE value for each model.

# LINEAR REGRESSION
best_lm <- collect_metrics(lm_fit)[1,]

# K NEAREST NEIGHBORS
best_knn <- select_by_one_std_err(knn_tune, metric="rmse", desc(neighbors))

# RIDGE REGRESSION
best_ridge <- select_by_one_std_err(ridge_tune, metric = "rmse", penalty)

# LASSO REGRESSION
best_lasso <- select_by_one_std_err(lasso_tune, metric = "rmse", penalty)

# ELASTIC NET
best_elastic <- select_by_one_std_err(elastic_tune, metric = "rmse", penalty, mixture)

# PRUNE DECISION TREE
best_tree <- select_by_one_std_err(tree_tune, metric = "rmse", cost_complexity)

# RANDOM FOREST
best_rf <- select_by_one_std_err(rf_tune, metric = "rmse", mtry, trees)


RMSE <- c(best_lm$mean, best_knn$mean, best_ridge$mean, best_lasso$mean, best_elastic$mean,
                 best_tree$mean, best_rf$mean)

Model <- c("Linear Regression", "KNN", "Ridge Regression", "Lasso Regression", "Elastic Net",
                 "prune Decision Tree", "Random Forest")

tibble(Model, RMSE) %>%
  arrange(RMSE)

Fitting to Training Data

As we found the best random forest model, we will use it to fit to the training data again, but this time we are using the whole training data set.

rf_final_workflow <- finalize_workflow(rf_workflow, best_rf)
rf_final_fit <- fit(rf_final_workflow, data = airbnb_train)

Testing the Model

Now, we can finally move on to testing the model on the testing data which hasn’t been used to train at all.

airbnb_metric <- metric_set(rmse)
augment(rf_final_fit, new_data = airbnb_test) %>%
  airbnb_metric(price, .pred)
## # A tibble: 1 × 3
##   .metric .estimator .estimate
##   <chr>   <chr>          <dbl>
## 1 rmse    standard        89.0

Our random forest model performs similarly on the testing with on the cross validation folds with 88.98507. As the range of our outcomes is 0 to 550, having the RMSE of 88.98507 might not be an ideal but not too bad either.

airbnb_tibble <- predict(rf_final_fit, new_data = airbnb_test %>% select(-price)) 
airbnb_tibble <- bind_cols(airbnb_tibble, airbnb_test %>% select(price))

airbnb_tibble %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=.pred, y=price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.1) +
  geom_abline(lty = 1) +
  xlab("prediction") +
  labs(title = "Predicticed Values vs. Actual Values") +
  theme_minimal()

If the price is predicted accrately, it will follow along the line. It seems that our prediction model is pretty accurate when the price is less than 200, but as the price gets higher, our prediction is a little bit off.

Since our model is random forest, we can create a variable importance plot. This plot will show which predictors are the most useful and wich predictors are the least useful.

rf_final_fit %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip() %>% 
  vip() + theme_minimal()

We can find that the three most useful predictors of price are whether or not the room type is private room, the number of days airbnb is available, and the number of listings the host has. Surprisingly, the least useful predictor is whether or not the room type is hotel.

Conclusion

Throughout the whole process fitting multiple models, we found that the best model to predict the price of Airbnb in LA is the random forest model. Even though this model doesn’t perform as well as we expected based on the RMSE, it makes sense that this model works best among the 7 models because the random forest model tends to work well with non-linear and large data without the risk of overfitting.

Linear regression, ridge regression, elastic net, and lasso regression models have similarly high RMSE values, which imply that those models don’t perform well. Since those models are types of linear model, we can assume that our dataset can’t be explained well by linear models.

If I were to continue with this project and improve the model, I would like to look more for the relationship between the locations and price. I assume that the reason why our model doesn’t perform ideally is that there are so many possible factors that can significantly affect the price other than the locations and room type. For example, the quality of interior, the number of bedrooms, how close it is to tourist spots, and transportation facilities around the place can affect the price a lot. Since it would be hard to measure those features in a form of dataset, the price prediction from the model can’t be perfectly accurate. However, our model can still be used to give hosts and guests some general range of the price based on our predictors such as neighborhood, room type, number of reviews, etc.
